In .NET 10, Android's `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` is fully deprecated and MAUI no longer supports it. The replacement is **`KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`**, which is enabled by default and automatically scrolls the focused input into view.

If it's not working for your layout, here's what to check:

**1. Make sure you haven't disabled it:**

```csharp
// Don't do this globally unless you have a reason:
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect();
```

**2. Wrap your page content in a `ScrollView`:**

The auto-scroll manager works best when your content is scrollable:

```xml
<ContentPage>
  <Grid RowDefinitions="*,Auto">
    <ScrollView Grid.Row="0">
      <CollectionView ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />
    </ScrollView>

    <!-- Input bar at bottom -->
    <Grid Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
      <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..."
             ReturnType="Send" />
    </Grid>
  </Grid>
</ContentPage>
```

**3. For Android specifically, set `AdjustPan` in your `MainActivity`:**

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan, ...)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

`AdjustPan` pans the window so the focused view is visible—it's not deprecated like `AdjustResize`.

**4. Edge-to-edge (if you're using it):** If your app opts into edge-to-edge display, you'll need to react to insets manually on Android:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
using AndroidX.Core.View;

ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
    Platform.CurrentActivity!.Window!.DecorView,
    new InsetListener());

class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        // Push your input bar up by imeInsets.Bottom pixels
        MessagingCenter.Send(new KeyboardMsg(imeInsets.Bottom), "kbd");
        return insets;
    }
}
#endif
```

**TL;DR:** Use `SoftInput.AdjustPan` on your `MainActivity` + keep `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` enabled (the default). That combination handles most chat-style layouts without any extra code.
